━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

SINGLE-FLOW — no multi-step files, no second run needed.

Step 1  Login  →  POST /api/auth/login
Step 2  Fetch  →  GET  /api/schedules           (paginated)
Step 3  Scan   →  flag expired=true OR stopDate in the past
Step 4  Report →  print clear table of problem schedules
Step 5  Approve→  interactive prompt (A=all / 1,3,5 / Q=quit)
Step 6  Fix    →  GET /api/schedules/{id}  then  PUT /api/schedules/{id}
· startDate = today
· stopDate  = today + 2 years
Step 7  Summary→  counts + timestamped JSON audit file
Step 8  Logout →  POST /api/auth/logout

STRATEGY ONE REST API FIELD REFERENCE  (v11.5.9 / Sep 2025)
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
GET /api/schedules  →  {“schedules”: […]}

Per schedule object:
id                   string   32-char GUID
name                 string
description          string
scheduleType         string   “time_based” | “event_based”
startDate            string   “YYYY-MM-DD”
stopDate             string   “YYYY-MM-DD”  (absent = no end date)
scheduleNextDelivery string   ISO-8601 | null when expired
expired              bool     true when stopDate < today
time                 object   recurrence block (time_based only)
└ recurrencePattern  string   “daily”|“weekly”|“monthly”|“yearly”
└ execution          object   executionPattern, startTime, …
└ daily/weekly/monthly/yearly  object
event                object   (event_based only)
└ id, name
acg                  int      access control flags

PUT /api/schedules/{id}
Send the full schedule object back with updated startDate / stopDate.
The server re-derives `expired` and `scheduleNextDelivery`.
Do NOT omit the `time` or `event` block — the server needs it.

